\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:6:\"line_1\";s:18:\"Writing Department\";s:6:\"line_2\";s:26:\"Loyola University Maryland\";s:6:\"line_3\";s:18:\"4501 N. Charles St\";s:4:\"city\";s:9:\"Baltimore\";s:5:\"state\";s:2:\"MD\";s:7:\"zipcode\";s:5:\"21210\";s:7:\"country\";s:3:\"USA\";s:8:\"latitude\";s:15:\"39.329015000000\";s:9:\"longitude\";s:16:\"-76.621587000000\";s:2:\"id\";s:2:\"13\";s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;s:5:\"order\";i:0;}}','a:1:{s:32:\"24da3632646f48edb2754a4f729cf450\";a:6:{s:4:\"type\";s:9:\"workphone\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:6:\"number\";s:12:\"410-617-2228\";s:2:\"id\";s:2:\"14\";s:5:\"order\";i:0;s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;}}','a:1:{s:32:\"c34aa666eab443c9b0338ceaf77360b6\";a:6:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"work\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:7:\"address\";s:19:\"poneill1@loyola.edu\";s:2:\"id\";s:2:\"13\";s:5:\"order\";i:0;s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;}}','','','a:1:{s:32:\"d1d1d518693940c0b8d0d58d21be02ca\";a:11:{s:4:\"type\";s:7:\"website\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:5:\"title\";s:18:\"Department Website\";s:3:\"url\";s:38:\"http://www.loyola.edu/academic/writing\";s:6:\"target\";s:3:\"new\";s:6:\"follow\";i:0;s:2:\"id\";s:2:\"17\";s:5:\"order\";i:0;s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;s:5:\"image\";b:0;s:4:\"logo\";b:0;}}','','','','Loyola\'s Writing department has been independent of English since the early 1980s. It began as a Writing and Media department, was renamed Communication for a few years in the early 2000s, and was split from Communication around 2005. It has a long history of contributing to the composition and rhetoric. For example, Barbara Walvoord, Lucille McCarthy and others conducted influential WAC/WID research at Loyola in the 1980s.\r\n\r\nOur students, rather than learning how to write within the structures of a single discipline, can explore, study, and practice a wide variety of forms including rhetoric, professional writing, poetry, fiction, and nonfiction prose. These forms foster a balance of analysis, precision of language, and creativity not found within many disciplines. Loyola\'s writing department offers a major, an interdisciplinary major, and a minor. The university-wide Writing Center is part of our department. We also have a rich assortment of co-curricular activities including a literary magazine, a reading series, internships and service-learning. The writing honor society, Pi Epsilon Pi, was founded at Loyola.\r\n\r\nYou can read more about our department\'s evolution and curriculum in the following chapter:\r\n\r\nO’Neill, Peggy and Barbara Mallonee. “Reforming and Transforming Writing in the Liberal Arts Context: The Writing Department at Loyola University Maryland.” <em>Writing Majors: Eighteen Program Profiles</em>. Eds. Greg Giberson, Jim Nugent, and Lori Ostergaard. Logan, UT: Utah State University Press, 2015. 74-61. Print.','','a:2:{s:5:\"entry\";a:1:{s:4:\"type\";s:12:\"organization\";}s:5:\"group\";a:1:{s:6:\"family\";a:0:{}}}',2,2,2,0,'approved'),(14,'2015-08-25 03:14:41','1440454481',0,'organization','public','university-of-florida','','','','','','','','University of Florida','University Writing Program','Creed','Greer','a:1:{s:12:\"756069178619\";a:14:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"work\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:6:\"line_1\";s:17:\"302 Tigert Hall  \";s:6:\"line_2\";s:14:\"PO Box 112020 \";s:6:\"line_3\";s:21:\"University of Florida\";s:4:\"city\";s:11:\"Gainesville\";s:5:\"state\";s:2:\"FL\";s:7:\"zipcode\";s:5:\"32611\";s:7:\"country\";s:3:\"USA\";s:8:\"latitude\";s:10:\"29.6494226\";s:9:\"longitude\";s:18:\"-82.33987439999999\";s:2:\"id\";N;s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;s:5:\"order\";i:0;}}','a:1:{s:12:\"588535567465\";a:5:{s:4:\"type\";s:9:\"workphone\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:6:\"number\";s:12:\"352-846-1138\";s:5:\"order\";i:0;s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;}}','a:1:{s:13:\"1286258553707\";a:5:{s:4:\"type\";s:4:\"work\";s:10:\"visibility\";s:6:\"public\";s:7:\"address\";s:14:\"cgreer@ufl.edu\";s:5:\"order\";i:0;s:9:\"preferred\";b:0;}}','','','a:1:{s:12